# Typer Guidance

## Project Context

- Python version: {{ python_version | default("detected by Akira") }}
- Package manager: {{ package_manager | default("detected by Akira") }}

## App Structure

- Use a single `typer.Typer()` app for small CLIs; introduce nested subapps only
  when command groups have separate lifecycles, options, or help surfaces.
- Put global options in an app callback and store shared state on
  `typer.Context.obj` so subcommands do not re-parse configuration.
- Use `no_args_is_help=True` for CLIs where running the bare command should
  show guidance instead of doing work.
- Keep command functions thin: parse CLI values, call application code, and
  translate results into user-facing output.

## Type Annotations As The Interface

- Prefer `Annotated[type, typer.Option(...)]` and
  `Annotated[type, typer.Argument(...)]`; avoid the older
  `param: type = typer.Option(...)` default style in new code.
- `Optional[str] = None` models an omitted value cleanly and avoids displaying a
  misleading default for flags that are intentionally absent.
- Use `typer.Argument` for required positional input with a stable meaning; use
  `typer.Option` for optional values, toggles, and anything with a default.
- Use option callback validators for cross-field validation that Typer cannot
  express with a single annotation.

## Output

- Use a module-level `console = Console()` and Rich methods throughout when the
  project has Rich available.
- Reserve `typer.echo()` for projects that intentionally avoid Rich.
- For failure paths, raise `typer.Exit(1)` after writing the error message;
  never call `sys.exit()` from command code.
- Keep JSON or machine-readable output isolated from styled console output so
  tests and automation can assert it reliably.

## Testing

- Use `typer.testing.CliRunner` instead of subprocess tests for command
  behavior.
- Pass `mix_stderr=False` when tests need to assert stdout and stderr
  separately.
- Assert exit code, stdout/stderr, and filesystem side effects; keep business
  logic tests below the CLI layer.

## Avoid

- `typer.echo()` when Rich is already part of the CLI stack.
- `sys.exit()` instead of `raise typer.Exit(code=1)`.
- Business logic embedded inside command functions.
- Positional `Argument` values for anything optional or with a default.
- Importing from `click` directly when Typer provides the equivalent.
